# Context

Test 5c established that all 234 severe failures have within-file lookback between 151 and 384 samples, with zero file-start-loaded cases. SEQ_LEN=30 sees at most 20% of the shortest loading phase. This sweep tests whether longer sequence windows resolve the catastrophic failures (particularly the idx=38180 cluster) and quantifies the diminishing-returns curve.

GRU-only. MLP at SEQ_LEN=400 would have input dimension 4000, which is not a meaningful comparison and would not replicate Hwangbo's architecture in any useful way.

# Task

Retrain the GRU at SEQ_LEN ∈ {267, 325, 372, 400}. These are the p50/p75/p95 percentiles of the within-file lookback distribution from Test 5c, plus one point beyond the observed max (384) to confirm saturation.

For each SEQ_LEN:
1. Retrain GRU with identical hyperparameters to v1 (Adam, LR=1e-4, OneCycleLR max_lr=1e-3, batch 64, patience 20, 200 epochs max, MSE loss, seed fixed). Only SEQ_LEN changes.
2. Save checkpoint to `checkpoints/seq_sweep/gru_L{N}.pt`.
3. Evaluate on the v1 test split. Reuse the v1 scaler — do not re-fit.
4. Run Test 2 regime classification.

Also include SEQ_LEN=30 as the baseline row (from v1), so the table is complete without re-training the baseline.

Produce `experiments/outputs/seq_len_sweep.md`:

